    <Entry>
      <ID>49</ID>
      <DefaultText>You can feel the pull of the intricate adra capillaries that rise up from the depths below the chamber. Many are bound up with the great pillar, and would pass to Woedica, but some are filled with the souls of the dead, bound for somewhere else entirely, and you know these are paths of rebirth.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>50</ID>
      <DefaultText>You reach out for Thaos' soul, and you can feel its frailty in defeat, its texture like a coarse and threadbare cloth on the brink of disintegration. You insinuate yourself between the threads, pushing the weaving apart, unraveling the stitching until it is bereft of structure, a formless heap bound together by nothing at all.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>51</ID>
      <DefaultText>You regard Thaos' soul, still and subdued, and your pronouncement seems to empower your spirit. Your will seems to you now a thick chain, and you wind it around Thaos, constraining all movement, eliminating any possible last means of resistance. 
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>52</ID>
      <DefaultText>You return to the landscape of Thaos' memory, to the vast terrain of deceptions and crippling despair, and you can feel your agency in this world now, an ability to reshape to the whims of your dominant will. 

You focus on a vision of pure emptiness, and your will becomes a swirling vortex around you, sweeping through the landscape and bearing away moments and lifetimes like some apocalyptic b&#238;a&#373;ac that would tear away the essence of the planet itself.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>54</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stretching your presence as far as your spirit will allow, you make contact with one such path, and between it and yourself, you open up what feels like a long tunnel, sheer and undulating like the gullet of some enormous beast.

You shift your focus to Thaos' soul, clinging weakly to its vanquished shell, and with all your concentration you wrench it free and send it hurtling through the channel until it passes into the adra vein and can be felt no more.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>55</ID>
      <DefaultText>In its midst you dedicate your focus to a single idea, and the idea is "shatter." 

You concentrate, and as you concentrate you feel a force building within your soul - an outward pressure that strains against containment, threatening to rupture your spirit. When you can contain it no more, you transfer it into Thaos' soul all at once and release it there, a detonation of will that expands in all directions, driving out the remnants of his essence, scattering it into nothingness.

You can feel his presence no more.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>56</ID>
      <DefaultText>You call to mind the eternal prison, the vast empty cavern and its cells of adra, vacated by souls that chose to betray themselves in order to escape an infinite abyss of hopeless self-reflection.

You choose a vacant pillar, and pour your consciousness into it, creating a perfect, inescapable hollow with space for one. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>57</ID>
      <DefaultText>And now you gather up Thaos' soul and bear it to the pillar like some bodiless jailer conjured by justice itself. You can feel its resistance now, the abject terror radiating from it, but your bindings will not be broken. 

When at last it is sealed away and you begin to recede back to your center, you could almost swear you hear a distant, wordless cry for mercy.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>58</ID>
      <DefaultText>The storm builds until the very crust of the world peels from the fabric of the soul that anchored it, and it is borne off into the sky until it is too distant to observe. 

The last thing you see is a white void, boundless in all directions, unfettered by the shackles of experience and doubt.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>59</ID>
      <DefaultText>In the stillness that follows, a single word echoes through your mind - a word you spoke when you were one with Thaos in an ancient memory. You realize it is the word that activates the machine.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>60</ID>
      <DefaultText>Aloth shakes his head, looking down at Thaos in pity and wonder. "All those lives. And at the end of them, he was no better than the very people he sought to guide. 

"A pity he would ever have to face that realization again."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>61</ID>
      <DefaultText>Aloth nods slowly. "I suppose we'll see if he can rise above that."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>62</ID>
      <DefaultText>Kana looks down at the body, his brows furrowed with thought. "All those lifetimes, spent to preserve a single, vital secret. I would expect a man to reconsider his choices after the first five hundred years." </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>63</ID>
      <DefaultText>"An end to doubt and certainty alike."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>65</ID>
      <DefaultText>"In his own way, Thaos must have truly believed he was caring for the people of Eora, protecting them from themselves. A pity his soul won't have a chance to reflect on his errors before it enters the Wheel."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>66</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Some acts cannot be forgiven, it seems."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>67</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Perhaps this is the best place in the world for Thaos, somewhere he can&#8217;t cause further harm. Still, you eventually found Iovara. What is a few thousand years to someone like him?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>68</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You've let him off too easily, Watcher. I would've left such scars on his soul that he'd have begged escape from the Wheel's turn."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>69</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You've let him off too easily, Watcher. I would've left such scars on his soul that he'd have begged escape from the Wheel's turn."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>70</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Some point, you have to look at the things your god is telling you to do and ask yourself if it's worth it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
